{meta: title When The Works All Done This Fall}
{meta: artist Marty Robbins}
{meta: composer D.J. O'Malley}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[C]A group of jolly cowboys discussing plans at [F]ease
One [G7]said I'll tell you something boys if you will listen [C]please
I'm an old cowpuncher and here I'm dressed in [F]rags
I [G7]used to be a tough one and go on great big [C]jags
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
I have got a home boys a good one you all [F]know
[G7]Although I haven't seen it since long long [C]ago
I'm going back to Dixie once more to see them [F]all
I'm [G7]going home to mother when the work's all done this [C]fall
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
That night this very cowboy went out to stand his [F]guard
The [G7]night was dark and stormy was raining very [C]hard
The cattle they got frightened and they rushed in wild [F]stampede
The [G7]cowboy tried to turn them while riding at full [C]speed
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
Riding in the darkness loudly he did [F]shout
[G7]Trying his best to stop them or turn the herd [C]about
His saddle horse did stumble and upon him it did [F]fall
Poor [G7]boy won't see his mother when the work's all done this [C]fall
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 5}
Fred you can take my saddle Jim you take my [F]bed
[G7]Johnny take my pistols after I am [C]dead
Think about me kindly as you look upon them [F]all
I'll [G7]not see my mother when the work's all done this [C]fall
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 6}
They buried Charlie at daybreak no tombstone at his [F]head
[G7]Nothing but a little board and this is what it [C]said
Charlie died at daybreak he died from a [F]fall
Poor [G7]boy won't see his mother when the work's all done this [C]fall
{end_of_verse}
